es, craft statutes, chronicle accounts, and challenges to single combat. The book also includes an extensive glossary, lavishly illustrated with fifty-two images of extant armour and weapons from the period, and contemporary artistic depictions from illuminated manuscripts and other sources. This book will therefore be of interest to a wide audience, from the living history practitioner, crafter, and martial artist, to students of literature, military history, art, and material culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArmor, Medieval. 0aMilitary art and sciencezEuropexHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aMilitary weaponszEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCharles VI.  aEdward II.  aEdward III.  aEurope.  aHEMA.  aHenry of Lancaster.  aRobert the Bruce.  aSir Philipe de Mézières.  aSir Roger Stanegrave.  aarchery.  aarmoury.  aaxe.  abreastplate.  acannon.  achainmail.  achivalry.  acraft.  acrossbow.  acrusades.  adagger.  afield guns.  agunpowder.  ahauberk.  ahelmet.  aheraldry.  ajoust.  aknights.  alance.  aliving history.  alongbow.  amace.  amen-at-arms.  ametallurgy.  ashields.  asiege engine.  asquires.  aswords.  atournament.  awar horses.1 aMoffat, Ralph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311143099740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800104563?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800104563423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800104563/original  a978-3-11-143099-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles